Find the determinant of the following 3x3 matrix: 

\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix} 
2 & 3 & -1 \\
4 & -2 & 1 \\
-5 & 1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

message_2:
To find the determinant of a 3x3 matrix, we can use the following formula:

det(A) = a(ei - fh) - b(di - fg) + c(dh - eg)

where a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, and i are the elements of the matrix:

\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix} 
a & b & c \\
d & e & f \\
g & h & i
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

In our case, the matrix is:

\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix} 
2 & 3 & -1 \\
4 & -2 & 1 \\
-5 & 1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

So, a = 2, b = 3, c = -1, d = 4, e = -2, f = 1, g = -5, h = 1, and i = 4.

Now, we can plug these values into the formula:

det(A) = 2((-2)(4) - (1)(1)) - 3((4)(4) - (1)(-5)) - (-1)((4)(1) - (-2)(-5))

det(A) = 2(-8 - 1) - 3(16 + 5) + 1(4 - 10)

det(A) = 2(-9) - 3(21) + 1(-6)

det(A) = -18 - 63 - 6

det(A) = -87

So, the determinant of the given matrix is -87.
